# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: beer-in-indonesia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Currently, there are no alcohol bans being enforced in Indonesia, with the exception of Aceh.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Since 2014, anyone found consuming alcohol or breaching the codes on moral conduct, whether residents or visitors to Aceh, could face between six and nine cane lashes.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In other parts of Indonesia, to appease the Islamic parties and pressure groups, the government agreed to apply mild restriction measures on alcohol, which includes high taxation and limited bans.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Indonesia is among the countries that apply high taxes on imported alcoholic beverages; in 2015, import tax on alcohol jumped to 150%.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Also in 2015, the Indonesian government banned the sale of alcohol from minimarkets and small shops, with the exception of Bali province, though sale was allowed in supermarkets, restaurants, bars, clubs and hotels.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Nevertheless, in more cosmopolitan Indonesian cities like Jakarta, Medan and Surabaya, and also in tourism hotspots such as Bali, Yogyakarta and Batam, alcoholic beverages are readily available, yet with higher prices, owing to the high tax applied upon alcoholic beverages.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In February 2016, Indonesian Malt Beverage Producers Association (GIMMI) called the House of Representatives to draft for comprehensive regulations on the chain of production and the marketing of alcoholic beverages, instead of total prohibition.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Since ancient times, local alcoholic beverages were developed by natives in the archipelago.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Some panels in 9th century Borobudur bas-reliefs depicted drink vendors, *warung* (small restaurant), and there is a panel depicting a building with people drinking (possibly alcoholic beverages), dancing and having fun, seeming to depict a tavern or lodging house.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] According to a Chinese source, Yingya Shenglan (c.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] 15th century) the people of Java in Majapahit kingdom drank wine made from palm sap called *tuak* (palm wine).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] However, by the 16th century Islam began to supplant Hinduism and Buddhism as the major religion in Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Since then, as a Muslim-majority country, Indonesian Muslims share Islamic dietary laws that prohibit alcoholic beverages.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Nevertheless, the local alcohol-drinking culture still survives, at least among less-religious members of society and among the non-Muslim community.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Certain ethno-cultural regions which are predominantly Christian are known for their affinity to alcohol-drinking traditions; such as the Batak, Torajan, Minahasan, Ambonese and Papuan.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Indonesia has its own traditional alcoholic beverages prepared by fermenting rice grain, gluten, sugar palm sap, and coconuts.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] According to culinary expert William Wongso, the culture of drinking distilled alcohol was never strong in Indonesia, with only a few regions having developed it.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In the Batak community in North Sumatra, *tuak* (palm liquor) is a compulsory drink in the celebrations and became a tradition in the community.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Batak tribes are predominantly of Christian Protestant faith, yet some of its clans are Muslim.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] A traditional Batak bar serving *tuak* is called a *lapo tuak*.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In the Toraja lands of South Sulawesi, their version of *tuak* — made from fermented sugar palm sap, is called *ballo*.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In Torajan traditional ceremonies, rituals and celebrations, *ballo* is always served, either as a prerequisite for the ritual; as an offering for ancestral spirits, as well as for drinks for guests.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Ballo* is also commonly consumed by the neighboring Bugis ethnic group.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In the Minahasa region of North Sulawesi, an almost identical palm liquor, also made from sugar palm sap, is called *saguer*.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In Nusa Tenggara and Maluku Islands the people also drink palm wine, locally known as *sopi*.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Also in the Minahasa region, the people drink a highly alcoholic drink called *cap tikus* (lit.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Cap tikus* is made from distilled *saguer* or *sopi* (palm wine), which increases its alcohol content.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] The origin of *cap tikus* brand is unclear.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] It is suggested that circa 1820s, prior to the 1830 Java War, the KNIL Minahasan legion found and bought distilled *saguer* or *sopi* sold in blue bottles embossed with the image of mouse sold by a Chinese merchant in Fort Amsterdam in Manado.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Today however, because of poor regulation on alcohol production in this region, this traditional home-made *cap tikus* industry is considered as an illegal beverage, due to the high prevalence of mortal alcohol poisoning.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Bottled *brem bali* (Balinese rice wine) and *arrack* are popular beverages in the Hindu-majority island of Bali.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Brem* is a brownish colored liquor with 5% alcohol.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] For Balinese people it has a religious significance too.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Brem*, *arak* and *tuak* are required for *tabuhan* (offerings) to the gods.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In Solo, Central Java, *ciu*, a local adaptation of Chinese wine, made from cider molasses of sugarcane is well known.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] It is linked to Solo's history as a sugar plantation and production center in colonial times.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] The Dutch Colonial state was established in Indonesia in the 1800s.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] The colonial Dutch brought their European drinking culture to the East Indies, most prominently with beer.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] The Heineken beer company established its brewery factory in Surabaya in 1929 during the Dutch colonial rule of Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] By the 1960s, Indonesians developed their own local brands of beer, which included Bintang Beer (nationalized from Heineken) and Anker Beer.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In April 2019, the East Nusa Tenggara provincial government supported the legal aspect of production and distribution of sopi, a local traditional alcoholic beverage.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] This policy is very likely to make sopi the first fully supported alcoholic product by the local government in Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] A Presidential regulation signed by Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono in 2013 gave legal cover to distribution of alcohol, it classified alcoholic beverages in Indonesia in three categories.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Drinks having an alcohol percentage less than 5% (A class), 5%–20% (B class) and more than 20% (C class).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] It was replacement of the 1997 decree after the Supreme Court abolished it following appeals from hard-line religious groups like the Islamic Defenders Front.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] The 2012 court ruling came after a draft bill proposed by the United Development Party (PPP) to completely ban the sale, production and consumption of alcohol in Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] However, the 2013 presidential regulation was welcomed by travel agencies in the wake of the harmful effects of the proposed draft on tourism.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Prices of wine and spirits in Indonesia increased by 140.5% and 154.4% respectively between 2009 and 2014.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In 2015 the government further hiked the import tariff on wine and spirits which nearly doubled the price of alcoholic beverages.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Some foreign companies which sell alcohol in Indonesia are Diageo, Pernod Ricard, Remy Cointreau and Bacardi.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] PT Multi Bintang is the largest domestic brewery of Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] As per market experts, because of various regulations, alcohol sales are declining in Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Bintang Beer of Multi Bintang brewery is the largest selling beer of Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Multi Bintang is a subsidiary of Heineken Asia Pacific.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In 2011, Bintang Beer won the Gold Medal for the Lager Beer Category and was awarded 'Champion Beer 2011' at the world's class beer competition, the Brewing Industry International Award (BIIA 2011) in London.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In 2014 Bintang Radler was introduced which was the first flavored beer produced domestically in Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Other major beer producers are Delta Djakarta known for its Anker Beer, and PT Bali Hai Brewery Indonesia known for its Bali Hai.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Indonesia also produces other brands, including San Miguel Beer and Asahi beer, under license.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Diageo manufactures Smirnoff and Captain Morgan products in Bali, which qualifies both brands for classification as locally produced spirits.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] The high prices of alcohol beverages in Indonesia, caused by high taxation and restrictions, has led to cases of illegal alcohol in the country.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] As the legal and imported alcoholic beverages become unaffordable, locals turn to illegal bootlegged alcohol for a cheaper drink.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] These illegal alcoholic drinks are known in Indonesian as *alkohol oplosan* (lit.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] "solved alcohol") and account for over 80% of the alcohol consumed in Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] These illicitly produced liquors which are traditionally home-made, are considered illegal by Indonesian law, due to the high incidence of deadly alcohol poisoning.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] The *lapen* liquor from Yogyakarta for example, is made from industrial alcohol of 85% volume mixed with water with a 1:4 or 5 alcohol to water ratio; then mixed with fruit essence as a flavoring agent.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In February 2010, 16 people died and 5 *lapen* sellers were arrested in Yogyakarta, due to alcohol poisoning and illicit alcohol production.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] In September 2010, three Russian Sukhoi fighter technicians died in Makassar from methanol poisoning in their drinks.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Yogyakarta residents were again affected by badly made alcohol in 2016.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-in-indonesia] Other traditionally made alcoholic spirits such as Solo's *ciu*, Manado's *cap tikus*, and some Balinese *arrack* are known as illegal alcohol, also due to the high incidence of alcohol poisoning.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] The southern boundary of this region corresponds to the −2 °C (28°F) January isotherm in lowlands.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] With the exception of Slovakia, Poland, Ukraine, and some regions of southern Russia, cultivation of grapes is impossible or very difficult.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] EU-countries preferring vodka produce over 70% of the EU's vodka.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] Vodka preference is sometimes associated exclusively with the Slavic countries of Central and Eastern Europe, as they are the historical homeland of vodka (Poland and Russia being the nations most often associated with the invention of the drink).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] Before the 19th century, vodka was considered very much a "people's drink" that was common among the peasantry who made up the majority of the population in most countries of the time, while the aristocracy preferred imported wines or other alcoholic drinks that were considered less plebeian.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] There are exceptions, such as Żubrówka, a type of Polish vodka that dates back to the 16th century, which became popular among the szlachta (nobility) as well as the peasantry as early as the 18th century.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] In his book about the Soviet Union, Alex de Jonge elaborates on his concept of "geoalcoholics".
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] In particular, he explains Russian peculiarities by their belonging to the vodka belt and the absence of the beer belt in the Soviet Union.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] Other than the prevalent hard liquor, the vodka belt is also characterised by a higher occurrence of binge drinking compared to the rest of Europe.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] Likewise, in his *Russia and the Russians*, historian Geoffrey Hoskins notes the distinct effect vodka culture has had on the countries of the former Russian Empire, creating drinking as a social problem on a different level from other European countries.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] In many countries traditionally preferring vodka, it has been supplanted by beer as the alcoholic drink of choice since the early 21st century.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] Residents of Finland and Sweden consume twice as much beer as vodka (in terms of pure alcohol).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] The Polish Beer-Lovers' Party (which won 16 seats in the Sejm in 1991) was founded on the notion of fighting alcoholism by a cultural abandonment of vodka for beer.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] And indeed in 1998, beer surpassed vodka as the most popular alcoholic drink in Poland.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] The "Schnellhardt compromise", proposed by Horst Schnellhardt, suggests that vodkas from other than cereals, potatoes and molasses, should be labeled to say "Vodka produced from".
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] Countries in Europe in which beer is historically the most popular alcoholic drink, informally known as the **beer belt** are located to the southwest of countries preferring vodka ("vodka belt") and to the northeast of the countries preferring wine ("wine belt").
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] These countries' geography is closely tied to the historical growing range of its two main ingredients, barley and hops.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] Barley was first domesticated during the Neolithic in the ancient Near East.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] It has been brewed into beer-like beverages for thousands of years and grown in most of Europe since ancient times.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] Hops are more narrowly distributed, preferring humid temperate climates, similar to potatoes.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] Originally, European "ale" (not yet called beer in Germanic languages) was produced without hops, which were introduced to Europe from the east.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] The first evidence of hops in Europe dates from 736 CE, in the Hallertau region of present-day Germany, although the first mention of the use of hops *in brewing* in that country was not until 1079.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] The westward spread of hops was slow, not reaching England until 1524.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] Ireland was still importing hops in the eighteenth century; more than 500 tons of English hops were imported through Dublin alone in 1752.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] In 1516, the Bavarian *Reinheitsgebot* ("Purity Law") established that barley, hops and water were the only allowable ingredients in beer (yeast was considered a by-product rather than an ingredient).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] This became the template for beers across Europe.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] While non-barley beers (e.g. wheat beer), and non-hopped-beers (e.g. flavoured with gruit) are still produced, across most of Europe "beer" is synonymous with barley and hops.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] Since the northern range of hops does not include most of Scandinavia or Russia (or much of Scotland), these areas, for the most part, are outside of the beer belt and lie in the vodka/whisky belt.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] There is quite a bit of overlap in these French regions, as well as in southwestern Germany, Luxembourg and most parts of Austria, due to the considerable consumption and cultivation of fine wine there, and Poland is also a part of the vodka belt.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] The same applies to Latvia and Lithuania (in a lesser extent to Estonia as well), where beer and honey beer has been a traditional drink for centuries and is a traditional part of celebrations like Jāņi and the Saint Jonas's Festival.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] In 2016, UNESCO inscribed Belgian beer culture on their list of the intangible cultural heritage of humanity.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] Countries in Europe in which wine is historically the most popular alcoholic drink, informally known as the **wine belt**, are located to the south of beer belt and vodka belt.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] The wine belt has been variously defined as approximately spanning 41–44°N, 30–50°N, and 35–50/51°N.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] Countries in the wine belt include Spain, Portugal, Italy, Greece, Georgia, Cyprus, Albania, Kosovo, North Macedonia, Serbia, Montenegro, Croatia, Bulgaria, San Marino, Switzerland, Romania, France, and Southern Federal District of Russia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] The countries of Austria, Hungary, and Slovenia, which themselves produce some highly-regarded wines, may sometimes be considered as part of the wine belt, but they overlap largely and are in line more with the Beer Belt instead.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] Additionally, Southwest England (if one classes cider as a wine analogue), parts of the Low Countries, southwestern Germany and parts of Austria could be considered to lie either within the belt or within an overlap region.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/alcohol-preferences-in-europe] A number of countries in Southeast Europe that fall within the wine belt also produce a variety of fruit brandies, many of which are considered their "national drink", such as Țuică, Rakia, and Pálinka.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] The **Archipelago Brewery** was a Singaporean brewery owned by Heineken Asia Pacific (formerly Asia Pacific Breweries).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] It labelled itself as "Singapore's Craft Brewery".
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] Archipel Brouwerij Compagnie (Archipelago Brewery Co.) was formed in Batavia (now known as Jakarta).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] The board was formed by the firm, Geo Wehry and Co.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] This company imported all by Beck brewery in Bremen to brew Koentji (key) beer.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] The first brewery was built in Batavia, it was made of steel framing, something in the Dutch Indies virtually not been done before.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] Wehry was a trading company, which started out in trading tobacco.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] Wehry was later merged with Borsumij and then merged into the still existing Hagemeyer that time in the Dutch East Indies was established.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] Archipelago opened a brewery on Alexandra Road in Singapore on 4 November 1933, in art-deco buildings designed by Hienrich Rudolf Arbenz, where it produced Anchor Beer.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] During World War II, the British deemed the brewery to be enemy territory due to its German ties and seized it in 1941.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] It was then bought by Malayan Breweries Ltd, which in 1990 was renamed Asia Pacific Breweries.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] In 2013, Asia Pacific Breweries merged to become Heineken Asia Pacific.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] Archipelago Brewery is currently Heineken Asia Pacific's craft brewing arm.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] The old Archipelago Brewery was re-commissioned on 24 July 2006, with international brewmaster, Fal Allen.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] Three variants of the Archipelago craft beers, namely Traveller's Wheat, Straits Pale and Traders Brown Ale were launched at Archipelago's flagship pub located on Circular Road in Singapore (now closed).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] The re-launch of Archipelago was consistent with Heineken Asia Pacific's objectives to add a new dimension to Singapore's beer industry; and to continue to grow its presence and stature locally.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] Archipelago Brewery produced boutique beers in small batches.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] In 2016, Archipelago Brewery brewed and sold 390,000 litres of beer.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] The Archipelago Brewery currently produces six permanent beers: Tropical Pale Ale, Singapore Blonde Ale, Belgian Wit, Summer IPA, Bohemian Lager and Irish Ale, in addition to limited edition or specialty beers.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] In May 2024, Heineken Asia Pacific announced it would be closing the brewery at the end of June that year.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/archipelago-brewery] The brewery created speciality brews which were sold as limited-release products, produced in much smaller quantities than the regular brews.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] The **Asahi Group Holdings, Ltd.** (アサヒグループホールディングス株式会社, *Asahi Gurūpu Hōrudingusu kabushiki gaisha*) is a Japanese beverage holding company headquartered in Sumida, Tokyo.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In 2024, the group had revenue of JPY 2.9 trillion.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] Asahi's business portfolio can be segmented as follows: alcoholic beverage business (40.5%), overseas business (32%), soft drinks business (17.2%), food business (5.4%) and "other" business (4.9%).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] Asahi, with a 37% market share, is the largest of the four major beer brewers in Japan followed by Kirin Beer with 34% and Suntory with 16%.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] Asahi has a 48.5% share of the Australian beer market.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In response to a maturing domestic Japanese beer market, Asahi broadened its geographic footprint and business portfolio through the acquisition of beer businesses in Western Europe and Central Eastern Europe.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] This has resulted in Asahi having a large market share in many European countries, such as a beer market share of 44% in the Czech Republic, 32% in Poland, 36% in Romania, and 18% in Italy.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] The predecessor of the company, Asahi Breweries (朝日麦酒株式会社), was established in 1889.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In 1893, it was reorganized as Ōsaka Breweries (大阪麦酒株式会社).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In 1906, Ōsaka Breweries merged with Nippon Breweries and Sapporo Breweries to form Dai-Nippon Breweries (大日本麦酒株式会社; lit.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] During World War I, German prisoners worked in the brewery.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] After World War II, the company was divided under the Elimination of Excessive Concentration of Economic Power Law by the Supreme Commander for the Allied Powers.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] Asahi Breweries (朝日麦酒株式会社) was separated from Nippon Breweries, which is now Sapporo Breweries.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In 1989, it was renamed to katakana (アサヒビール株式会社).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In 2011, Asahi Breweries changed its name to Asahi Group Holdings, a holding company, and established Asahi Breweries Ltd as a subsidiary.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In 1990, Asahi acquired a 19.9% stake in Australian brewery giant Elders IXL, which later became the Foster's Group and was subsequently sold to SABMiller.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In 2009, Asahi acquired the Australian beverages unit Schweppes Australia, now known as Asahi Beverages.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In early 2009, Asahi acquired 19.9% of Tsingtao Brewery from Anheuser-Busch InBev for $667 million.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] The sale made Asahi Breweries, Ltd. the second largest shareholder in Tsingtao behind only the Tsingtao Brewery Group.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In July 2011, Asahi acquired New Zealand juice maker Charlie's and the water and juice divisions of Australian beverage company P&N Beverages.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In August 2011, Asahi acquired New Zealand's Independent Liquor, maker of Vodka Cruiser and other alcoholic beverages, for ¥97.6 billion.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In May 2013, its New Zealand operations expanded with the purchase of retail chain Mill Liquorsave.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] Also, Asahi acquired the Australian brands and assets of Cricketers Arms and Mountain Goat Brewery in 2013 and 2015, respectively.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] After Inbev's acquisition of SABMiller in October 2016, InBev agreed to sell the former SABMiller Ltd.'s Eastern European businesses and relevant assets in Poland, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary and Romania to Asahi for US $7.3 billion.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] The deal closed on 21 December 2016 and included beer brands such as Pilsner Urquell, Velkopopovický Kozel, Topvar, Tyskie, Lech, Dreher and Ursus.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In 2017, the company sold its 19.9% stake of Tsingtao Brewery for $937 million.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In 2019, the company bought Fuller's beer business from Fuller, Smith & Turner plc for an enterprise value of £250 million.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] The assets sold comprised the entirety of Fuller's beer, cider and soft drinks brewing and production, wine wholesaling, as well as the distribution thereof and also includes the Griffin Brewery, Cornish Orchards, Dark Star Brewing and Nectar Imports.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In May 2020, the Australian Foreign Investment Review Board approved the company's $16 billion bid for Carlton & United Breweries, and the deal will see Asahi ending up with about 48.5 per cent share of the Australian beer market.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In January 2024, Asahi Europe & International (AEI), the international arm of Asahi Group Holdings, acquired Octopi Brewing, a contract beverage production and co-packing facility based in Waunakee, Wisconsin.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] In September 2025, a ransomware attack on The Asahi group, caused a system outage and forced the company to halt production at most of its 30 factories.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] On October 3 it was announced that they were days away from running out of their most popular beer, Asahi Super Dry.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] The company's primary beer, from 1957 through the late 1980s, was *Asahi Gold* (overtaking *Asahi Draft*, its original formula, which remains in production).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] However, *Asahi Super Dry*, introduced in 1987, is now the company's flagship beer brand.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] Asahi Breweries' headquarters in Tokyo were designed by French designer Philippe Starck.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/asahi-beer] The Beer Hall is considered one of Tokyo's most recognizable modern structures.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali is the only Hindu-majority province in Indonesia, with 86.40% of the population adhering to Balinese Hinduism.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] It is renowned for its highly developed arts, including traditional and modern dance, sculpture, painting, leather, metalworking, and music.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Indonesian International Film Festival is held every year in Bali.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Other international events that have been held in Bali include Miss World 2013, the 2018 Annual Meetings of the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank Group, and the 2022 G20 summit.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In March 2017, Tripadvisor named Bali as the world's top destination in its Traveler's Choice award, which it earned once again in January 2021 and 2026.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali is part of the Coral Triangle, an area with high diversity of marine species, mainly fish and turtles.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In this area alone, over 500 reef-building coral species can be found.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] For comparison, this is about seven times as many as in the entire Caribbean.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali is the home of the Subak irrigation system, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] It is also home to a unified confederation of kingdoms composed of 10 traditional royal Balinese houses, each house ruling a specific geographic area.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The confederation is the successor of the Bali Kingdom.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The royal houses, which originated before Dutch colonisation, are not recognised by the government of Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The name *Bali* is attested in ancient Balinese inscriptions as part of the compound *Vāli-dvīpa* (or *Wāli-dvīpa*), where Sanskrit *dvīpa* (Sanskrit: द्वीप) means "island".
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] One of the earliest attestations of *Vāli-dvīpa* occurs in the Belanjong (Blanjong) pillar inscription, dated to Saka year 835 / Phalguna month, under King Sri Kesari Warmadewa (c.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The precise meaning of the element *Vāli* in *Vāli-dvīpa* is not certain.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali was inhabited around 2000 BC by Austronesian peoples who migrated originally from the island of Taiwan to Southeast Asia and Oceania through Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Culturally and linguistically, the Balinese are closely related to the people of the Indonesian archipelago, Malaysia, Brunei, the Philippines, and Oceania.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Stone tools dating from this time have been found near the village of Cekik in the island's west.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In ancient Bali, nine Hindu sects existed: the Pasupata, Bhairawa, Siwa Shidanta, Vaishnava, Bodha, Brahma, Resi, Sora, and Ganapatya.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Each sect revered a specific deity as its personal Godhead.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Inscriptions from 896 and 911 do not mention a king until 914, when Sri Kesarivarma, a contemporary of the Kesari dynasty in the Kalinga Kingdom of ancient India, is mentioned.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] They also reveal an independent Bali, with a distinct dialect, being influenced by the Sanskrit and Pali languages, where Buddhism and Shaivism were practiced simultaneously.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Mpu Sindok's great-granddaughter, Mahendradatta (Gunapriyadharmapatni), married the Bali king Udayana Warmadewa (Dharmodayanavarmadeva) around 989, giving birth to Airlangga around 1001.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] This marriage also brought more Hinduism and Javanese culture to Bali.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Princess Sakalendukirana appeared in 1098.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Suradhipa reigned from 1115 to 1119, and Jayasakti from 1146 until 1150.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Jayapangus appears on inscriptions between 1178 and 1181, while Adikuntiketana and his son Paramesvara appear in 1204.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Balinese culture was strongly influenced by Indian, Chinese, and particularly Kalinga Hindu culture, beginning around the 1st century AD.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The name *Bali dwipa* ("Bali island") has been discovered from various inscriptions, including the Blanjong pillar inscription written by Sri Kesari Warmadewa in 914 AD, and mentioning **Walidwipa**.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] It was during this time that the people developed their complex irrigation system, *subak,* to grow rice in wet-field cultivation.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Some religious and cultural traditions still practiced today can be traced to this period.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Hindu-Buddhist Majapahit Empire (1293–1520 AD) on eastern Java founded a Balinese colony in 1343.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The uncle of Hayam Wuruk is mentioned in the charters of 1384–86.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Mass Javanese immigration to Bali occurred in the next century when the Majapahit Empire fell in 1520.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali's government then became an independent collection of Hindu kingdoms, which led to a Balinese national identity and major enhancements in culture, arts, and economy.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The nation with various kingdoms became independent for up to 386 years until 1906, when the Dutch subjugated and repulsed the natives for economic control and took it over.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The first known European contact with Bali is thought to have been made in 1512, when a Portuguese expedition led by Antonio Abreu and Francisco Serrão sighted its northern shores.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] It was the first expedition of a series of bi-annual fleets to the Moluccas, which, throughout the 16th century, travelled along the coasts of the Sunda Islands.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali was also mapped in 1512, in the chart of Francisco Rodrigues, aboard the expedition.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In 1585, a ship foundered off the Bukit Peninsula and left a few Portuguese in the service of Dewa Agung.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In 1597, the Dutch merchant-explorer Cornelis de Houtman arrived at Bali, and the Dutch East India Company was established in 1602.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Dutch government expanded its control across the Indonesian archipelago during the second half of the 19th century.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Dutch political and economic control over Bali began in the 1840s on the island's north coast when the Dutch pitted various competing Balinese realms against each other.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In the late 1890s, struggles between Balinese kingdoms on the island's south were exploited by the Dutch to increase their control.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In June 1860, the famous Welsh naturalist, Alfred Russel Wallace, travelled to Bali from Singapore, landing at Buleleng on the north coast of the island.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Wallace's trip to Bali was instrumental in helping him devise his Wallace Line theory.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Wallace Line is a faunal boundary that runs through the strait between Bali and Lombok.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Dutch mounted large naval and ground assaults at the Sanur region in 1906 and were met by the thousands of members of the royal family and their followers, who, rather than yield to the superior Dutch force, committed ritual suicide (*puputan*) to avoid the humiliation of surrender.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Despite Dutch demands for surrender, an estimated 200 Balinese killed themselves rather than surrender.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In the Dutch intervention in Bali, a similar mass suicide occurred in the face of a Dutch assault in Klungkung.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Afterward, the Dutch governors exercised administrative control over the island, but local control over religion and culture generally remained intact.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Dutch rule over Bali came later and was never as well established as in other parts of Indonesia, such as Java and Maluku.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In the 1930s, anthropologists Margaret Mead and Gregory Bateson, artists Miguel Covarrubias and Walter Spies, and musicologist Colin McPhee all spent time here.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Their accounts of the island and its peoples created a Western image of Bali as "an enchanted land of aesthetes at peace with themselves and nature".
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Soon after, Western tourists began to visit the island.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The film, which mostly consisted of scenes of topless Balinese women, was a great success in 1932, and was perhaps the main catalyst for the popularity of Bali among tourists.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Dutch also dedicated significant efforts to implement *Baliseering* (lit.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] 'Balinization') politics to maintain traditions on the island, as well as preventing the Islamization of the Islamic sultanates from Java and banning Christian missionaries' activities.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Imperial Japan occupied Bali during World War II.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] It was not originally a target in their Netherlands East Indies Campaign; however, as the airfields on Borneo were inoperative due to heavy rains, the Imperial Japanese Army decided to occupy Bali, which did not suffer from comparable weather.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The island had no regular Royal Netherlands East Indies Army (KNIL) troops.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] There was only a Native Auxiliary Corps *Prajoda* (Korps Prajoda) consisting of about 600 native soldiers and several Dutch KNIL officers under the command of KNIL Lieutenant Colonel W.P.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] On 19 February 1942, the Japanese forces landed near the town of Sanoer (Sanur) and the island was quickly captured.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] During the Japanese occupation, a Balinese military officer, I Gusti Ngurah Rai, formed a Balinese 'freedom army'.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The harsh treatment of the Balinese by the Japanese occupation forces fomented more resentment than the former Dutch colonial rulers.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In 1945, Bali was liberated by the British 5th Infantry Division under the command of Major-General Robert Mansergh, who took the Japanese surrender.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Once Japanese forces had been repatriated, the island was handed over to the Dutch the following year.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In 1946, the Dutch constituted Bali as one of the 13 administrative districts of the newly proclaimed State of East Indonesia, a rival state to the Republic of Indonesia, which was proclaimed and headed by Sukarno and Hatta.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali was included in the "Republic of the United States of Indonesia" when the Netherlands recognised Indonesian independence on 29 December 1949.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The first governor of Bali, Anak Agung Bagus Suteja, was appointed by President Sukarno in 1958, when Bali became a province.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The 1963 eruption of Mount Agung killed thousands, created economic havoc, and forced many displaced Balinese to be transmigrated to other parts of Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Mirroring the widening of social divisions across Indonesia in the 1950s and early 1960s, Bali saw conflict between supporters of the traditional caste system and those rejecting this system.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Politically, the opposition was represented by supporters of the Indonesian Communist Party (PKI) and the Indonesian Nationalist Party (PNI), with tensions and ill-feeling further increased by the PKI's land reform programmes.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] A purported coup attempt in Jakarta was averted by forces led by General Suharto.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The army became the dominant power as it instigated a violent anti-communist purge backed by Western powers, in which the army blamed the PKI for the coup.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Most estimates suggest that at least 500,000 people were killed across Indonesia, with an estimated 80,000 killed in Bali, equivalent to 5% of the island's population.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] With no Islamic forces involved as in Java and Sumatra, upper-caste PNI landlords led the extermination of PKI members.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] As a result of the 1965–66 massacres, Suharto was able to manoeuvre Sukarno out of the presidency.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] His "New Order" government re-established relations with Western countries.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The pre-war Bali, as "paradise," was revived in a modern form.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The resulting large growth in tourism has led to a dramatic increase in Balinese standards of living and significant foreign exchange earned for the country.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] A bombing in 2002 by militant Islamists in the tourist area of Kuta killed 202 people, mostly foreigners.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] This attack, and another in 2005, severely reduced tourism, producing much economic hardship on the island.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] On 9 July 2008, for the first time in Bali's history, the election for governor and vice governor of Bali was democratically elected by the people of Bali directly.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] On 27 November 2017, Mount Agung erupted five times, causing the evacuation of thousands, disrupting air travel, and causing much environmental damage.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Further eruptions also occurred between 2018 and 2019.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] On 15–16 November 2022, with the 2022 G20 Bali summit, the seventeenth meeting of the Group of Twenty (G20) was held in Nusa Dua.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The island of Bali lies 3.2 km (2.0 mi) east of Java, and is approximately 8 degrees south of the equator.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali and Java are separated by the Bali Strait.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Its population density was roughly 798 people/km2 (2,070 people/mi2) in mid 2024.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali's central mountains include several peaks over 2,000 metres (6,600 feet) in elevation and active volcanoes such as Mount Batur.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The highest is Mount Agung (3,031 m; 9,944 ft), known as the "mother mountain", which is an active volcano rated as one of the world's most likely sites for a massive eruption within the next 100 years.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In late 2017, Mount Agung started erupting and large numbers of people were evacuated, temporarily closing the island's airport.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Mountains range from centre to the eastern side, with Mount Agung the easternmost peak.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali's volcanic nature has contributed to its exceptional fertility, and its tall mountain ranges provide the high rainfall that supports the highly productive agricultural sector.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] South of the mountains is a broad, steadily descending area where most of Bali's large rice crop is grown.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The northern side of the mountains slopes more steeply to the sea and is the main coffee-producing area of the island, along with rice, vegetables, and cattle.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The longest river, Ayung River, flows approximately 75 km (47 mi) (see List of rivers of Bali).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The island is surrounded by coral reefs.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Beaches in the south tend to have white sand, while those in the north and west have black sand.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali has no major waterways, although the Ho River is navigable by small *sampan* boats.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Black sand beaches between Pasut and Klatingdukuh are being developed for tourism, but apart from the seaside temple of Tanah Lot, they are not yet used for significant tourism.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The largest city is the provincial capital, Denpasar, near the southern coast.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali's second-largest city is the old colonial capital, Singaraja, which is located on the north coast and whose urban area is home to around 150,000 people in 2024.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Other important cities include the beach resort, Kuta, which is practically part of Denpasar's urban area, and Ubud, situated at the north of Denpasar, which is regarded as the island's cultural centre.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Three small islands lie to the immediate south-east and all are administratively part of the Klungkung regency of Bali: Nusa Penida, Nusa Lembongan and Nusa Ceningan.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] These islands are separated from Bali by the Badung Strait.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] To the east, the Lombok Strait separates Bali from Lombok and marks the biogeographical division between the fauna of the Indomalayan realm and the distinctly different fauna of Australasia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The transition is known as the Wallace Line, named after Alfred Russel Wallace, who first proposed a transition zone between these two major biomes.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] When sea levels dropped during the Pleistocene ice age, Bali was connected to Java and Sumatra and to the mainland of Asia and shared the Asian fauna, but the deep water of the Lombok Strait continued to keep Lombok Island and the Lesser Sunda archipelago isolated.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Being just 8 degrees south of the equator, Bali has a fairly even climate all year round.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Average year-round temperature stands at around 30 °C (86 °F) with a humidity level of about 85%.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Daytime temperatures at low elevations vary between 20 and 33 °C (68 and 91 °F), but the temperatures decrease significantly with increasing elevation.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The west monsoon is in place from approximately October to April, and this can bring significant rain, particularly from December to March.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] During the rainy season, there are comparatively fewer tourists seen in Bali.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] During the Easter and Christmas holidays, the weather is very unpredictable.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Outside of the monsoon period, humidity is relatively low and any rain is unlikely in lowland areas.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali lies just to the west of the Wallace Line, and thus has a fauna that is Asian in character, with very little Australasian influence, and has more in common with Java than with Lombok.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] An exception is the yellow-crested cockatoo, a member of a primarily Australasian family.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] There are around 280 species of birds, including the critically endangered Bali myna, which is endemic.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Until the early 20th century, Bali was possibly home to several large mammals: banteng, leopard and the endemic Bali tiger.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The banteng still occurs in its domestic form, whereas leopards are found only in neighbouring Java, and the Bali tiger is extinct.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The last definite record of a tiger on Bali dates from 1937 when one was shot, though the subspecies may have survived until the 1940s or 1950s.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Pleistocene and Holocene megafaunas include banteng and giant tapir (based on speculations that they might have reached up to the Wallace Line), and rhinoceros.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Squirrels are quite commonly encountered, less often is the Asian palm civet, which is also kept in coffee farms to produce kopi luwak.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bats are well represented, perhaps the most famous place to encounter them remaining is the Goa Lawah (Temple of the Bats) where they are worshipped by the locals and also constitute a tourist attraction.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] They also occur in other cave temples, for instance at Gangga Beach.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The crab-eating macaque, known locally as "kera", is quite common around human settlements and temples, where it becomes accustomed to being fed by humans, particularly in any of the three "monkey forest" temples, such as the popular one in the Ubud area.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] They are also quite often kept as pets by locals.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The second monkey, endemic to Java and some surrounding islands such as Bali, is far rarer and more elusive and is the Javan langur, locally known as "lutung".
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] They occur in a few places apart from the West Bali National Park.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] They are born an orange colour, though they would have already changed to a more blackish colouration by their first year.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In Java, however, there is more of a tendency for this species to retain its juvenile orange colour into adulthood, and a mixture of black and orange monkeys can be seen together as a family.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Other rarer mammals include the Sunda leopard cat, Sunda pangolin and black giant squirrel.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Snakes include the king cobra and reticulated python.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The water monitor can grow to at least 1.5 m (4.9 ft) in length and 50 kg (110 lb) and can move quickly.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Dolphins are commonly encountered on the north coast near Singaraja and Lovina.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] A team of scientists surveyed from 29 April 2011, to 11 May 2011, at 33 sea sites around Bali.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] They discovered 952 species of reef fish of which 8 were new discoveries at Pemuteran, Gilimanuk, Nusa Dua, Tulamben and Candidasa, and 393 coral species, including two new ones at Padangbai and between Padangbai and Amed.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The average coverage level of healthy coral was 36% (better than in Raja Ampat and Halmahera by 29% or in Fakfak and Kaimana by 25%) with the highest coverage found in Gili Selang and Gili Mimpang in Candidasa, Karangasem Regency.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Among the larger trees the most common are: banyan trees, jackfruit, coconuts, bamboo species, acacia trees and also endless rows of coconuts and banana species.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Numerous flowers can be seen: hibiscus, frangipani, bougainvillea, poinsettia, oleander, jasmine, water lily, lotus, roses, begonias, orchids and hydrangeas exist.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] On higher grounds that receive more moisture, for instance, around Kintamani, certain species of fern trees, mushrooms and even pine trees thrive well.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Other plants with agricultural value include: salak, mangosteen, corn, Kintamani orange, coffee and water spinach.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Over-exploitation by the tourist industry has led to 200 out of 400 rivers on the island drying up.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Research suggests that the southern part of Bali would face a water shortage.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] To ease the shortage, the central government plans to build a water catchment and processing facility at Petanu River in Gianyar.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The 300 litres capacity of water per second will be channelled to Denpasar, Badung and Gianyar in 2013.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] A 2010 Environment Ministry report on its environmental quality index gave Bali a score of 99.65, which was the highest score of Indonesia's 33 provinces.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The score considers the level of total suspended solids, dissolved oxygen, and chemical oxygen demand in water.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Erosion at Lebih Beach has seen seven metres (23 feet) of land lost every year.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Decades ago, this beach was used for holy pilgrimages with more than 10,000 people, but they have now moved to Masceti Beach.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In 2017, a year when Bali received nearly 5.7 million tourists, government officials declared a "garbage emergency" in response to the covering of 3.6-mile stretch of coastline in plastic waste brought in by the tide, amid concerns that the pollution could dissuade visitors from returning.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Indonesia is one of the world's worst plastic polluters, with some estimates suggesting the country is the source of around 10 per cent of the world's plastic waste.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] On 3 February 2026, Bali launched a major beach clean up after President Prabowo Subianto's criticisms of the Bali's growing waste problem.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Hundreds of personnel from the Bali Police and the local military joined students and volunteers to collect rubbish from two of the island’s most popular tourist beaches: Kuta and Kedonganan in Badung Regency.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The governor is the highest officeholder in the Bali provincial government with the vice governor being the second highest officeholder.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Governor of Bali is responsible for the territory of the Province of Bali.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The current governor in office in the province of Bali is I Wayan Koster who was first being elected in the 2018 Bali gubernatorial election accompanied by his first running mate at that time Tjokorda Oka Artha Ardana Sukawati (Cok Ace).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Koster is the 8th governor of Bali, since the province was formed into the province of Bali in 1958 based on Law Number 64 of 1958.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Koster and Cok Ace were inaugurated by the president of the Republic of Indonesia at that time Joko Widodo, at the State Palace, Jakarta on September 5, 2018, for the five years term of office (2018–2023).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] After his term of office ended, Sang Made Mahendra Jaya was inaugurated as acting governor of Bali on September 5, 2023 with a limited authority in the government.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] After re-elected in 2024 I Wayan Koster and I Nyoman Giri Prasta was inaugurated on February 20, 2025 at the State Palace by the incumbent President of Indonesia Prabowo Subianto for the five years term of office (2025–2030).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In the national legislature, Bali is represented by nine members, with a single electoral district covering the whole province.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Bali Regional House of Representatives (DPRD), the provincial legislature, has 55 members.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The province's politics has historically been dominated by the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P), which has won by far the most votes in every election in Bali since the first free elections in 1999, it currently forms the ruling government in the province.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] They are tabulated below with their areas and their populations at the 2010 census and the 2020 census, together with the official estimates as at mid 2024 and the Human Development Index for each regency and city.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The province forms one of Indonesia's 84 national electoral districts to elect members to the Indonesian parliament.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The **Bali Electoral District** consists of all of the 8 regencies in the province, together with the city of Denpasar, and elects 9 members to the People's Representative Council.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In the 1970s, the Balinese economy was largely agriculture-based in terms of both output and employment.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Tourism is now the largest single industry in terms of income, and as a result, Bali is one of Indonesia's wealthiest regions.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In 2003, around 80% of Bali's economy was tourism related.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] By the end of June 2011, the rate of non-performing loans of all banks in Bali were 2.23%, lower than the average of Indonesian banking industry non-performing loan rates (about 5%).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The economy, however, suffered significantly as a result of the terrorist bombings in 2002 and 2005.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The tourism industry has since recovered from these events.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Although tourism produces the GDP's largest output, agriculture is still the island's biggest employer.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Fishing also provides a significant number of jobs.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali is also famous for its artisans who produce a vast array of handicrafts, including batik and ikat cloth and clothing, wooden carvings, stone carvings, painted art and silverware.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Notably, individual villages typically adopt a single product, such as wind chimes or wooden furniture.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Arabica coffee production region is the highland region of Kintamani near Mount Batur.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Generally, Balinese coffee is processed using the wet method.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] This results in a sweet, soft coffee with good consistency.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Typical flavours include lemon and other citrus notes.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Many coffee farmers in Kintamani are members of a traditional farming system called Subak Abian, which is based on the Hindu philosophy of "Tri Hita Karana".
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] According to this philosophy, the three causes of happiness are good relations with God, other people, and the environment.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Subak Abian system is ideally suited to the production of fair trade and organic coffee production.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Arabica coffee from Kintamani is the first product in Indonesia to request a geographical indication.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In 2025, Bali received 6,948,754 international tourists, an increase of 9.72% compared to 2024..
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In 1963, the Bali Beach Hotel in Sanur was built by Sukarno and boosted tourism in Bali.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Before the Bali Beach Hotel construction, there were only three significant tourist-class hotels on the island.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Construction of hotels and restaurants began to spread throughout Bali.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Tourism further increased in Bali after the Ngurah Rai International Airport opened in 1970.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Buleleng regency government encouraged the tourism sector as one of the mainstays for economic progress and social welfare.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The tourism industry is primarily focused in the south, while also significant in the other parts of the island.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The United States government lifted its travel warnings in 2008.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Australian government issued an advisory on Friday, 4 May 2012, with the overall level of this advisory lowered to 'Exercise a high degree of caution'.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Swedish government issued a new warning on Sunday, 10 June 2012, because of one tourist who died from methanol poisoning.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Australia last issued an advisory on Monday, 5 January 2015, due to new terrorist threats.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] An offshoot of tourism is the growing real estate industry.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali's real estate has been rapidly developing in the main tourist areas of Kuta, Legian, Seminyak, and Oberoi.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Most recently, high-end 5-star projects are under development on the Bukit peninsula, on the island's south side.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Expensive villas are being developed along the cliff sides of south Bali, with commanding panoramic ocean views.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Foreign and domestic, many Jakarta individuals and companies are fairly active, and investment into other areas of the island also continues to grow.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Land prices, despite the worldwide economic crisis, have remained stable.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In the last half of 2008, Indonesia's currency had dropped approximately 30% against the US dollar, providing many overseas visitors with improved value for their currencies.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali's tourism economy survived the terrorist bombings of 2002 and 2005, and the tourism industry has slowly recovered and surpassed its pre-terrorist bombing levels; the long-term trend has been a steady increase in visitor arrivals.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In 2010, Bali received 2.57 million foreign tourists, which surpassed the target of 2.0–2.3 million tourists.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The average occupancy of starred hotels achieved 65%, so the island still should be able to accommodate tourists for some years without any addition of new rooms/hotels, although at the peak season some of them are fully booked.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali received the Best Island award from Travel and Leisure in 2010.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali won because of its attractive surroundings (both mountain and coastal areas), diverse tourist attractions, excellent international and local restaurants, and the friendliness of the local people.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Balinese culture and its religion are also considered the main factor of the award.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] One of the most prestigious events that symbolize a strong relationship between a god and its followers is Kecak dance.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] According to BBC Travel released in 2011, Bali is one of the World's Best Islands, ranking second after Santorini, Greece.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In 2006, Elizabeth Gilbert's memoir *Eat, Pray, Love* was published, and in August 2010 it was adapted into the film *Eat Pray Love*.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] It took place at Ubud and Padang-Padang Beach in Bali.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Both the book and the film fuelled a boom in tourism in Ubud, the hill town and cultural and tourist centre that was the focus of Gilbert's quest for balance and love through traditional spirituality and healing.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In January 2016, after musician David Bowie died, it was revealed that in his will, Bowie asked for his ashes to be scattered in Bali, conforming to Buddhist rituals.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] He had visited and performed in several Southeast Asian cities early in his career, including Bangkok and Singapore.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Since 2011, China has displaced Japan as the second-largest supplier of tourists to Bali, while Australia still tops the list while India has also emerged as a greater supplier of tourists.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Chinese tourists increased by 17% in 2011 from 2010 due to the impact of ACFTA and new direct flights to Bali.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In January 2012, Chinese tourists increased by 222.18% compared to January 2011, while Japanese tourists declined by 23.54% year on year.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali is a very popular tourist destination for Indians.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Bali authorities reported the island had 2.88 million foreign tourists and 5 million domestic tourists in 2012, marginally surpassing the expectations of 2.8 million foreign tourists.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Based on a Bank Indonesia survey in May 2013, 34.39 per cent of tourists are upper-middle class, spending between $1,286 and $5,592, and are dominated by Australia, India, France, China, Germany and the UK.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Some Chinese tourists have increased their levels of spending from previous years.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] 30.26 per cent of tourists are middle class, spending between $662 and $1,285.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In 2017 it was expected that Chinese tourists would outnumber Australian tourists.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In January 2020, 10,000 Chinese tourists cancelled trips to Bali due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Because of the COVID-19 pandemic travel restrictions, Bali welcomed 1.07 million international travelers in 2020, most of them between January and March, which is −87% compared to 2019.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In the first half of 2021, they welcomed 43 international travelers.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The pandemic presented a major blow on Bali's tourism-dependent economy.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] On 3 February 2022, Bali reopened again for the first foreign tourists after 2 years of being closed due to the pandemic.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In 2022 Indonesia's Minister of Health, Budi Sadikin, stated that the tourism industry in Bali will be complemented by the medical industry.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] At the beginning of 2023, the governor of Bali demanded a ban on the use of motorcycles by tourists.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] This happened after a series of accidents.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Wayan Koster proposed to cancel the violators' visas.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The move sparked widespread outrage on social media.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Ngurah Rai International Airport is located near Jimbaran, on the isthmus at the southernmost part of the island.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] A coastal road circles the island, and three major two-lane arteries cross the central mountains at passes reaching 1,750 m in height (at Penelokan).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The Ngurah Rai Bypass is a four-lane expressway that partly encircles Denpasar.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] There is a car ferry between Gilimanuk on the west coast of Bali to Ketapang on Java which started running in the 1930s.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Two bus systems exist: Trans Sarbagita and Trans Metro Dewata.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In December 2010 the Government of Indonesia invited investors to build a new Tanah Ampo Cruise Terminal at Karangasem, Bali with a projected worth of $30 million.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] On 17 July 2011, the first cruise ship (Sun Princess) anchored about 400 metres (1,300 feet) away from the wharf of Tanah Ampo harbour.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The current pier is only 154 metres (505 feet) but will eventually be extended to 300 to 350 metres (980–1,150 feet) to accommodate international cruise ships.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The harbour is safer than the existing facility at Benoa and has a scenic backdrop of east Bali mountains and green rice fields.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The tender for improvement was subject to delays, and as of July 2013 the situation was unclear with cruise line operators complaining and even refusing to use the existing facility at Tanah Ampo.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] A memorandum of understanding was signed by two ministers, Bali's governor and Indonesian Train Company to build 565 kilometres (351 miles) of railway along the coast around the island.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] As of July 2015, no details of these proposed railways have been released.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In 2019 it was reported in *Gapura Bali* that Wayan Koster, governor of Bali, "is keen to improve Bali's transportation infrastructure and is considering plans to build an electric rail network across the island".
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] On 16 March 2011 (Tanjung) Benoa port received the "Best Port Welcome 2010" award from London's "Dream World Cruise Destination" magazine.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] Government plans to expand the role of Benoa port as export-import port to boost Bali's trade and industry sector.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In 2013, The Tourism and Creative Economy Ministry advised that 306 cruise liners were scheduled to visit Indonesia, an increase of 43 per cent compared to the previous year.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] In May 2011, an integrated Area Traffic Control System (ATCS) was implemented to reduce traffic jams at four crossing points: Ngurah Rai statue, Dewa Ruci Kuta crossing, Jimbaran crossing and Sanur crossing.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] ATCS is an integrated system connecting all traffic lights, CCTVs and other traffic signals with a monitoring office at the police headquarters.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] It has successfully been implemented in other ASEAN countries and will be implemented at other crossings in Bali.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] On 21 December 2011, construction started on the Nusa Dua-Benoa-Ngurah Rai International Airport toll road, which will also provide a special lane for motorcycles.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] This has been done by seven state-owned enterprises led by PT Jasa Marga with 60% of the shares.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] PT Jasa Marga Bali Tol will construct the 9.91-kilometre-long (6.16-mile) toll road (totally 12.7 kilometres (7.89 miles) with access road).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The construction is estimated to cost Rp.2.49 trillion ($273.9 million).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The project goes through 2 kilometres (1 mile) of mangrove forest and through 2.3 kilometres (1.4 miles) of beach, both within 5.4 hectares (13 acres) area.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] The elevated toll road is built over the mangrove forest on 18,000 concrete pillars that occupied two hectares of mangrove forest.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] This was compensated by the planting of 300,000 mangrove trees along the road.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] On 21 December 2011, the Dewa Ruci 450-metre (1,480-foot) underpass has also started on the busy Dewa Ruci junction near Bali Kuta Galeria with an estimated cost of Rp136 billion ($14.9 million) from the state budget.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] On 23 September 2013, the Bali Mandara Toll Road was opened, with the Dewa Ruci Junction underpass being opened previously.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p01] To solve chronic traffic problems, the province will also build a toll road connecting Serangan with Tohpati, a toll road connecting Kuta, Denpasar, and Tohpati, and a flyover connecting Kuta and Ngurah Rai Airport.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] In 2021, the Indonesian Ministry of Tourism estimated that there were 109,801 foreigners living on Bali, with most originating from Russia, United States, Australia, United Kingdom, Germany, Japan, France, Italy, India, and the Netherlands.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] A DNA study in 2005 by Karafet et al., found that 84% of Balinese Y-chromosomes are of likely Austronesian origin, 12% of likely Indian origin and 2% of likely Melanesian origin.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] According to a recent genetic study, the Balinese, together with the Javanese and Sundanese, have a significant admixture of Austroasiatic and Austronesian ancestries.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The majority of the population inhabiting the province of Bali are the local ethnic, namely the Balinese and indigenous Bali Aga people.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The Balinese have a cultural richness that is known worldwide, so that Bali is the main destination for foreign tourists to Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] In addition to the rich beaches, the culture that is of interest in Bali is its dances, such as the Kecak dance, festivals such as Ogoh-ogoh, and others.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The largest ethnic group outside the Balinese people is the Javanese people.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Pre-modern Bali had four castes, but with a "very strong tradition of communal decision-making and interdependence".
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The four castes have been classified as Sudra (Shudra), Wesia (Vaishyas), Satria (Kshatriyas) and Brahmana (Brahmin).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] In Bali, the Shudra (locally spelt *Soedra*) has typically been the temple priests, though depending on the demographics, a temple priest may also be from the other three castes.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] In most regions, it has been the Shudra who typically make offerings to the gods on behalf of the Hindu devotees, chant prayers, recite *meweda* (Vedas), and set the course of Balinese temple festivals.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] About 86.40% of Bali's population adheres to Balinese Hinduism, formed as a combination of existing local beliefs and Hindu beliefs from mainland Southeast Asia and South Asia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The Balinese people and Bali Aga are generally Hindu with some being Muslim (3.24%) and Christian (1.26%).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The Javanese, Sundanese, Sasak, and Malay people are generally Muslim and some are also Hindu or Christian.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Meanwhile, people from East Nusa Tenggara, as well as people of the Papua, Batak, Chinese and some other Indonesian ethnic groups that aren't traditionally Muslim are generally Christian, with small minority are Hindu and Muslim.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The village of Blimbing Sari in the Melaya district of Jembrana Regency, not far from Gilimanuk Port, is Christian, and the residents there are native Balinese, but the church is shaped like a Hindu temple.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The general beliefs and practices of *Agama Hindu Dharma* mix ancient traditions and contemporary pressures placed by Indonesian laws that permit only monotheist belief under the national ideology of *Pancasila*.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Traditionally, Hinduism in Indonesia had a pantheon of deities and that tradition of belief continues in practice; further, Hinduism in Indonesia granted freedom and flexibility to Hindus as to when, how and where to pray.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] However, officially, the Indonesian government considers and advertises Indonesian Hinduism as a monotheistic religion with certain officially recognised beliefs that comply with its national ideology.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Indonesian school textbooks describe Hinduism as having one supreme being, Hindus offering three daily mandatory prayers, and Hinduism as having certain common beliefs that in part parallel those of Islam.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Some scholars contest whether these Indonesian government recognised and assigned beliefs to reflect the traditional beliefs and practices of Hindus in Indonesia before Indonesia gained independence from Dutch colonial rule.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Balinese Hinduism has roots in Indian Hinduism and Buddhism, which arrived through Java.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Hindu influences reached the Indonesian Archipelago as early as the first century.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Historical evidence is unclear about the diffusion process of cultural and spiritual ideas from India.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Java legends refer to Saka-era, traced to 78 AD.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Stories from the Mahabharata Epic have been traced in Indonesian islands to the 1st century; however, the versions mirror those found in the southeast Indian peninsular region (now Tamil Nadu and southern Karnataka and Andhra Pradesh).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The Bali tradition adopted the pre-existing animistic traditions of the indigenous people.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] This influence strengthened the belief that the gods and goddesses are present in all things.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Every element of nature, therefore, possesses its power, which reflects the power of the gods.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] A rock, tree, dagger, or woven cloth is a potential home for spirits whose energy can be directed for good or evil.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Balinese Hinduism is deeply interwoven with art and ritual.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Ritualising states of self-control are a notable feature of religious expression among the people, who for this reason have become famous for their graceful and decorous behavior.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Apart from the majority of Balinese Hindus, there also exist Chinese immigrants whose traditions have melded with that of the locals.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] As a result, these Sino-Balinese embrace their original religion, which is a mixture of Buddhism, Christianity, Taoism, and Confucianism, and find a way to harmonise it with the local traditions.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Hence, it is not uncommon to find local Sino-Balinese during the local temple's *odalan*.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Moreover, Balinese Hindu priests are invited to perform rites alongside a Chinese priest in the event of the death of a Sino-Balinese.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Nevertheless, the Sino-Balinese claim to embrace Buddhism for administrative purposes, such as their Identity Cards.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The Roman Catholic community has a diocese, the Diocese of Denpasar that encompasses the province of Bali and West Nusa Tenggara and has its cathedral located in Denpasar.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Balinese and Indonesian are the most widely spoken languages in Bali, and the vast majority of Balinese people are bilingual or trilingual.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The most common spoken language around the tourist areas is Indonesian, as many people in the tourist sector are not solely Balinese, but migrants from Java, Lombok, Sumatra, and other parts of Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The Balinese language is heavily stratified due to the Balinese caste system.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Kawi and Sanskrit are also commonly used by some Hindu priests in Bali, as Hindu literature was mostly written in Sanskrit.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] English and Chinese are the next most common languages (and the primary foreign languages) of many Balinese, owing to the requirements of the tourism industry, as well as the English-speaking community and huge Chinese-Indonesian population.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Other foreign languages, such as Japanese, Korean, French, Russian or German, are often used in multilingual signs for foreign tourists.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Bali is renowned for its diverse and sophisticated art forms, such as painting, sculpture, woodcarving, handcrafts, and performing arts.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Balinese cuisine is also distinctive, and unlike the rest of Indonesia, pork is commonly found in Balinese dishes such as Babi Guling.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Balinese percussion orchestra music, known as *gamelan*, is highly developed and varied.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Balinese performing arts often portray stories from Hindu epics such as the Ramayana but with heavy Balinese influence.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Famous Balinese dances include *pendet*, *legong*, *baris*, *topeng*, *barong*, *gong kebyar*, and *kecak* (the monkey dance).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Bali boasts one of the most diverse and innovative performing arts cultures in the world, with paid performances at thousands of temple festivals, private ceremonies, and public shows.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] In 2018 Governor I Wayan Koster issued Bali Governor's Regulation No.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] 79 of 2018 which mandated that city officials wear traditional Balinese dress, such as that made of *songket*.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] 4 of 2021 which specified the use of Endek fabrics, and was expanded to high-ranking individuals in the private sector and other institutions.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Most temples have an inner courtyard and an outer courtyard which are arranged with the inner courtyard furthest *kaja*.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] These spaces serve as performance venues since most Balinese rituals are accompanied by any combination of music, dance, and drama.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The performances that take place in the inner courtyard are classified as *wali*, the most sacred rituals which are offerings exclusively for the gods, while the outer courtyard is where *bebali* ceremonies are held, which are intended for gods and people.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Lastly, performances meant solely for the entertainment of humans take place outside the temple's walls and are called *bali-balihan*.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] This three-tiered system of classification was standardised in 1971 by a committee of Balinese officials and artists to better protect the sanctity of the oldest and most sacred Balinese rituals from being performed for a paying audience.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Tourism, Bali's chief industry, has provided the island with a foreign audience that is eager to pay for entertainment, thus creating new performance opportunities and more demand for performers.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The impact of tourism is controversial since before it became integrated into the economy, the Balinese performing arts did not exist as a capitalist venture, and were not performed for entertainment outside of their respective ritual context.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Since the 1930s sacred rituals such as the *barong* dance have been performed both in their original contexts, as well as exclusively for paying tourists.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] This has led to new versions of many of these performances that have developed according to the preferences of foreign audiences; some villages have a *barong* mask specifically for non-ritual performances and an older mask that is only used for sacred performances.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Throughout the year, there are many festivals celebrated locally or island-wide according to the traditional calendars.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The Hindu New Year, *Nyepi*, is celebrated in the spring by a day of silence.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] On this day everyone stays at home and tourists are encouraged (or required) to remain in their hotels.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] On the day before New Year, large and colourful sculptures of *Ogoh-ogoh* monsters are paraded and burned in the evening to drive away evil spirits.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Other festivals throughout the year are specified by the Balinese *pawukon* calendrical system.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Celebrations are held for many occasions such as a tooth-filing (coming-of-age ritual), cremation or *odalan* (temple festival).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] One of the most important concepts that Balinese ceremonies have in common is that of *désa kala patra*, which refers to how ritual performances must be appropriate in both the specific and general social context.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Many ceremonial art forms such as *wayang kulit* and *topeng* are highly improvisatory, providing flexibility for the performer to adapt the performance to the current situation.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Many celebrations call for a loud, boisterous atmosphere with much activity, and the resulting aesthetic, *ramé*, is distinctively Balinese.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Often two or more *gamelan* ensembles will be performing well within earshot, and sometimes compete with each other to be heard.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Likewise, the audience members talk amongst themselves, get up and walk around, or even cheer on the performance, which adds to the many layers of activity and the liveliness typical of *ramé*.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Balinese society continues to revolve around each family's ancestral village, to which the cycle of life and religion is closely tied.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Coercive aspects of traditional society, such as customary law sanctions imposed by traditional authorities such as village councils (including "kasepekang", or shunning) have risen in importance as a consequence of the democratisation and decentralisation of Indonesia since 1998.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Other than Balinese sacred rituals and festivals, the government presents Bali Arts Festival to showcase Bali's performing arts and various artworks produced by the local talents that they have.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] It is held once a year, from the second week of June until the end of July.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Southeast Asia's biggest annual festival of words and ideas Ubud Writers and Readers Festival is held at Ubud in October, which is participated by the world's most celebrated writers, artists, thinkers, and performers.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] One unusual tradition is the naming of children in Bali.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] In general, Balinese people name their children depending on the order they are born, and the names are the same for both males and females.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Bali was the host of Miss World 2013 (63rd edition of the Miss World pageant).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] It was the first time Indonesia hosted an international beauty pageant.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] In 2022, Bali also co-hosted Miss Grand International 2022 along with Jakarta, West Java, and Banten.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Bali has hosted several milestone regional and sectoral gatherings, including foundational ASEAN summits.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Key agreements signed on the island include the 1976 Declaration of ASEAN Concord and the Treaty of Amity and Cooperation in Southeast Asia, as well as the Bali Concord II (2003) and Bali Concord III (2011).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] It also serves as the venue for the East Asia Summit's "Bali Principles" for mutually beneficial relations.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The province has been a focal point for global environmental and trade governance.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] It hosted the 2007 UNFCCC COP13, which produced the Bali Road Map, and the 2013 APEC Leaders' Week.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Additionally, the WTO Ninth Ministerial Conference adopted the "Bali Package" on trade facilitation in 2013.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Bali also anchors regional governance architectures through recurring platforms like the Bali Process on people smuggling and the Bali Democracy Forum.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] In 2022, the UN’s Global Platform for Disaster Risk Reduction was held on the island.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] More recently, Bali has hosted the Multilateral Naval Exercise Komodo (MNEK).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The 2025 iteration involved 38 countries and 19 foreign warships at Tanjung Benoa.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] These drills occurred amid regional tensions in the South China Sea regarding maritime claims, including China's "nine-dash line" which a 2016 arbitral tribunal under UNCLOS found had no legal basis.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Bali is a major world surfing destination with popular breaks dotted across the southern coastline and around the offshore island of Nusa Lembongan.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] As part of the Coral Triangle, Bali, including Nusa Penida, offers a wide range of dive sites with varying types of reefs, and tropical aquatic life.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Bali was the host of 2008 Asian Beach Games.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] It was the second time Indonesia hosted an Asia-level multi-sport event, after Jakarta held the 1962 Asian Games.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] In 2023, Bali was the location for a major eSports event, the Dota 2 Bali Major, the third and final Major of the Dota Pro Circuit season.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The event was held at the Ayana Estate and the Champa Garden, and it was the first time that a Dota Pro Circuit Major was held in Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] In football, Bali is home to Bali United football club, which plays in Liga 1.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] The team was relocated from Samarinda, East Kalimantan to Gianyar, Bali.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Harbiansyah Hanafiah, the main commissioner of Bali United explained that he changed the name and moved the home base because there was no representative from Bali in the highest football tier in Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] Another reason was due to local fans in Samarinda preferring to support Pusamania Borneo F.C. rather than Persisam.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/bali-p02] In June 2012, Subak, the irrigation system for paddy fields in Jatiluwih, central Bali was listed as a Natural UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The founding of Batavia by the Dutch in 1619, on the site of the ruins of Jayakarta, led to the establishment of a Dutch colony; Batavia became the center of the Dutch East India Company's trading network in Asia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Monopolies on local produce were augmented by non-indigenous cash crops.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] To safeguard their commercial interests, the company and the colonial administration absorbed surrounding territory.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Batavia is on the north coast of Java, in a sheltered bay, on a land of marshland and hills crisscrossed with canals.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The city had two centers: Oud Batavia (the oldest part of the city) and Weltevreden (the relatively newer city), on higher ground to the south.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] It was a European colonial city for about 320 years until 1942, when the Dutch East Indies was occupied by Japan during World War II.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] During the Japanese occupation and after Indonesian nationalists declared independence on 17 August 1945, the city was known as Jakarta.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] It remained internationally known by its Dutch name until Indonesia achieved full independence in 1949, when the city was renamed Djakarta, and eventually Jakarta.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Amsterdam merchants embarked on an expedition to the East Indies archipelago in 1595 under the command of Cornelis de Houtman.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The English East India Company's first voyage in 1602, commanded by James Lancaster, arrived in Aceh and sailed on to Bantam.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] There, Lancaster was allowed to build a trading post which was the center of English trade in the East Indies archipelago until 1682.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The Dutch government granted the Dutch East India Company (VOC) a monopoly on Asian trade in 1602.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] A year later, the first permanent Dutch trading post in the East Indies archipelago was established in Bantam, West Java.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Prince Jayawikarta gave Dutch merchants permission to build a wooden warehouse and houses on the east bank of the Ciliwung river opposite Jayakarta in 1610, and the outpost was established the following year.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] As Dutch power increased, Jayawikarta allowed the English to build houses on the west bank of the Ciliwung and a fort near his customs office to maintain a balance of power.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Tensions between Prince Jayawikarta and the Dutch escalated until 1618, when Jayawikarta's soldiers besieged the Dutch fortress containing the Nassau and Mauritius warehouse.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] An English fleet of 15 ships arrived under Thomas Dale, former governor of the colony of Virginia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] After a sea battle, newly appointed Dutch governor Jan Pieterszoon Coen escaped to the Moluccas to seek support; the Dutch had taken over the first of the Portuguese forts there in 1605.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Dutch garrison commander Pieter van den Broecke and five other men were arrested during negotiations, since Jayawikarta believed that he had been deceived by the Dutch.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Jayawikarta and the English then forged an alliance.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The Dutch army was on the verge of surrendering to the English when, in 1619, the Sultanate of Banten sent a group of soldiers to summon Jayawikarta.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Jayawikarta's agreement with the English had not been approved by the Bantenese authorities.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The conflict between Banten and Jayawikarta and the tense relationship between Banten and the English provided a new opportunity for the Dutch.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Coen returned from the Moluccas with reinforcements on 28 May 1619, razing Jayakarta to the ground two days later and expelling its population.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Only the Luso-Sundanese padrão remained.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Jayawikarta retreated to Tanara, in the interior of Banten, where he later died.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The Dutch established a closer relationship with Banten and assumed control of the port, which became the regional Dutch center of power.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The region which became Batavia came under Dutch control in 1619, initially as an expansion of the original Dutch fort and a new building on the ruins of the former Jayakarta.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Coen decided to expand the original fort into a larger fortress on 2 July 1619, and sent plans for Batavia Castle to the Netherlands on 7 October of that year.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The castle was larger than the previous one, with two northern bastions protecting it from a maritime attack.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The Nassau and Mauritius warehouses were expanded with the erection of an eastern fort extension, overseen by Commander Van Raay, on 12 March 1619.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Although Coen wanted to name the new settlement Nieuw-Hoorn after Hoorn (his birthplace), he was prevented from doing so by the board of the VOC.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Batavia was chosen as the new name of the fort and settlement, and a naming ceremony was held on 18 January 1621.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] It was named after the Batavi Germanic tribe, which inhabited the Batavian region during the Roman Empire; at the time, it was believed that the tribe was the ancestors of the Dutch people.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Jayakarta was called Batavia for over 300 years.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] There were three governmental administrations in the Batavia region.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Initial authority was established in 1609 and became the colonial *High Government*, consisting of the Governor-General and the Council of the Indies.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The urban (or civil) administration of the city of Batavia was established in 1620.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] On 24 June 1620, two company officials and three free citizens (or burghers) were appointed to the first College of Aldermen.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The local rural administration, formed in 1664, became fully functional in 1682.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The Javanese people were prohibited from settling in Batavia from the time of its founding in 1619.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] From its founding, Batavia was planned in a well-defined layout.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Three trenches were dug east of the Ciliwung River in 1619, its first Dutch-made canals.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The canals were named (from south to north) Leeuwengracht, Groenegracht, and Steenhouwersgracht.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The castle area begins in a former field north of Steenhouwersgracht, in which a town market was established.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The first church and town hall were built c.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Around 1627, the three canals were connected with the Tijgersgracht canal.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The Prinsestraat, originally the street leading to the castle, became an urban center connecting the castle's south gate with the city hall.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Eastern Batavia was protected by a long canal which linked the castle moat and the Ciliwung riverbend, and ran at a slight angle to Tijgersgracht.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The canal cost over 160,000 real, which was paid mostly by the Chinese instead of the company (who had strengthened the castle with slave and prison labor).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The short-lived outer canal was redesigned several years after the 1628–1629 siege of Batavia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Sultan Agung (king of the Mataram Sultanate) gained control of most of Java by defeating Surabaya in 1625.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] On 27 August 1628, Agung began the siege of Batavia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] After heavy losses in his first attempt, he retreated and launched a second offensive the following year.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] This also failed; the Dutch fleet destroyed his supplies and ships in the harbors of Cirebon and Tegal.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Mataram troops, starving and decimated by illness, retreated again.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Agung then moved east, attacking Blitar, Panarukan and the Blambangan Kingdom in eastern Java (a vassal state of the Balinese kingdom of Gelgel).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] After the siege, it was decided that Batavia needed a stronger defense system.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Based on the work of Flemish mathematician and military engineer Simon Stevin, Governor-General Jacques Specx designed a moat and city wall; extensions of the wall were built west of Batavia, and the city was completely enclosed.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] In 1656, due to a conflict with Banten, the Javanese were not allowed to live within the city walls and settled outside Batavia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The Chinese and the Mardijkers were the only non-Dutch settlers within the walled city.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] A 1659 truce with Banten enabled the city to grow, and more bamboo houses were built.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Bamboo houses and livestock were banned in 1667, and the wealthy Dutch built tall houses and canals.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The region was an important source of food crops and building materials.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The VOC established a local government in 1664, which became fully functional in 1682.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Chinese inhabitants began to cultivate sugarcane.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Large-scale cultivation negatively impacted the environment, and Batavia's northern area experienced coastal erosion.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The canals required extensive maintenance, with frequent closures for dredging.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Residents of the Ommelanden lived in country houses or ethnic kampungs governed by a headman.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Batavia's sugar industry declined during the 1730s, with rising unemployment and social disorder.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] In 1739, there were 10,574 Chinese people living in the Ommelanden.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Tensions grew as the colonial government attempted to restrict Chinese immigration with deportations to Ceylon and South Africa.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The Chinese, afraid that they would be thrown overboard to drown, rioted.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Ten thousand Chinese were killed from 9 to 22 October 1740.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The few surviving Chinese inhabitants were moved to Glodok, outside the city walls, the following year.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] In 1789, the Americans visited and were permitted through formal applications to trade.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] After the VOC went bankrupt and was dissolved in 1800, the Batavian Republic nationalized its debts and possessions and expanded its territorial claims into a colony known as the Dutch East Indies.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Batavia evolved from a regional company headquarters into the colony's capital.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] In 1808, Herman Willem Daendels decided to leave the dilapidated, unhealthy Old Town.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] A new town center was built further south, on the Weltevreden estate.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Batavia became a city with two centers; Kota was the business hub with offices and warehouses of shipping and trading companies, and Weltevreden was home to the government, military, and shops.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The centers were connected by the Molenvliet Canal and a road alongside the canal.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Under British rule, Daendels was replaced by Stamford Raffles.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] In 1811, Raffles—who was employed by the British East India Company as secretary to the governor of Malacca—decided to take over the government in Batavia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] One reason was to prevent the French from stepping in completely, since Napoleon had nominated Daendels (who worked closely with the French).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] In 1816, the Dutch returned to rule the region.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Europeans were brought to the archipelago to establish a colony on vacant land, triggering wars in Java and Sumatra.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Large numbers of troops were brought into the Dutch Indies to suppress unrest (particularly on Sumatra) and extend Dutch government influence beyond Java.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] However, the Dutch never conquered the entire archipelago.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The development of Weltevreden as the colony's administrative center continued, gradually shifting the center of Batavia south from Oud Batavia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] A new Indies Empire style of architecture emerged; white-plastered villas with a large front porch were built, especially around the Koningsplein and at Weltevreden.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] This newer part of Batavia generally had a more open look than Oud Batavia's developed, canal cityscape.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Unlike the first half of the 19th century, the second half of the century was a peaceful period characterized by economic and technological expansion and a stable government.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] In 1856, the region's first telegraph line was installed between Batavia and Buitenzorg.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] In 1859, Batavia was connected to Singapore with the Dutch East Indies' first international telegraph connection.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The city completed its first gasworks two years later, and its streets were lit with gas by 1862.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The first trams and telephones came in 1882.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Horse-drawn tram, introduced to Batavia in 1869, were upgraded to steam power in 1882 and electricity in 1900.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The city's first railway also began in 1869, and the line from Batavia to Buitenzorg was completed in 1873.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The city's first ice house was built in 1870.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The 1869 opening of the Suez Canal increased the need for a new port.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The port of Tanjung Priok was completed in 1885, replacing the centuries-old, inadequate Sunda Kelapa, significantly increasing trade and tourism in Batavia and the Dutch East Indies.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The Cultivation System (*cultuurstelsel*) was a mid-19th-century Dutch government policy which required a portion of agricultural production to be export crops.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Indonesian historians refer to it as *tanam paksa* (enforced planting).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The 1870 abolition of the Cultivation System led to the rapid development of private enterprise in the Dutch East Indies.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] A number of trading companies and financial institutions were established on Java, particularly in Batavia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The Old Town's deteriorating structures were replaced with offices, usually along the Ciliwung River.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Private companies owned (or managed) plantations, oil fields, and mines.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The island's first railway line opened in 1867, and railway stations were built in urban centers such as Batavia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Schools, hospitals, factories, offices, trading companies, and post offices were established throughout the city.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Improvements in Batavia's transportation, health, and technology encouraged more Dutch people to move to the capital, and Batavian society became increasingly Dutch.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The city traded with Europe, and increased shipping led to the construction of a new harbor at Tanjung Priok between 1877 and 1883.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Foreigners were known locally as totoks, distinguishing new Chinese arrivals from the peranakans.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Many totoks adopted Indonesian culture, wearing kebayas, sarongs, and summer dresses.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] By the end of the 19th century, Batavia's population was 115,887 people; of these, 8,893 were Europeans, 26,817 were Chinese and 77,700 were indigenous islanders.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The city's expanding commercial activity led to the immigration of large numbers of Dutch employees and rural Javanese to Batavia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The 1905 population of Batavia and its surrounding area reached 2.1 million, including 93,000 Chinese people, 14,000 Europeans, and 2,800 Arabs.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] This growth resulted in an increased demand for housing, and land prices soared.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] New houses were built close together, and kampung settlements filled spaces between the houses.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Settlements, built with little regard for the region's tropical conditions, resulted in overcrowding, poor sanitation, and an absence of public amenities.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Old Batavia's abandoned moats and ramparts experienced a boom during the period, as trading companies were established along the Ciliwung.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The old city soon re-established itself as a commercial center, with 20th- and 17th-century buildings adjacent to one another.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The Dutch Ethical Policy was introduced in 1901, expanding educational opportunities for the indigenous population of the Dutch East Indies.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] In 1924, a law school was founded in Batavia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The city's population in the 1930 census was 435,000.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The University of Batavia was established in 1941, and later became the University of Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] In 1946, the Dutch colonial government established the Nood Universiteit (Emergency University) in Jakarta.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The following year, its name was changed to Universiteit van Indonesië (UVI).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] After the Indonesian National Revolution the government established Universiteit Indonesia, a state university, in Jakarta in February 1950.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Its name was later changed to Universitas Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Volksraad member Mohammad Husni Thamrin criticized the colonial government for ignoring the kampungs and catering to the wealthy in Menteng.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] In 1909, Tirto Adhi Soerjo founded the Islamic Commercial Union in Batavia to support Indonesian merchants.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] In 1920, Oemar Said Tjokroaminoto and Agus Salim established a committee in Batavia to support the Ottoman Caliphate.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Spies warned the Dutch about a planned revolt in 1926, and Communist Party of Indonesia (PKI) leaders were arrested.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Andries Cornelis Dirk de Graeff replaced Dirk Fock as governor-general, and uprisings in Batavia, Banten, and Priangan were quickly crushed.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Armed Communists occupied the Batavia telephone exchange for one night before they were captured.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The Dutch sent prisoners to Banden and to a penal colony at Boven-Digoel in West New Guinea, where many died of malaria.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Sukarno and the Study Club founded the Indonesian Nationalist Association (which became the Indonesian National Party and later joined the Partai Sarekat Islam, Budi Utomo, and the Surabaya Study Club to form the Union of Indonesian Political Associations) on 4 July 1927.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] A youth congress was held in Batavia in October 1928, and the groups began referring to the city as Jakarta.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] They demanded Indonesian independence, displayed the red-and-white flag, and sang the Indonesian national anthem written by Wage Rudolf Supratman.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The Dutch banned the flag, the national anthem, and the words "Indonesia" and "Indonesian".
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] On 5 March 1942, Batavia fell to the Japanese.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The Dutch formally surrendered to the Japanese occupation forces on 9 March 1942, and the colony's government was transferred to Japan.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The economic situation and the physical condition of Indonesian cities deteriorated during the occupation.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Buildings were converted to internment camps for the Dutch.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] After the Japanese defeat in 1945, the region experienced a period of transition and upheaval during the Indonesian struggle for independence.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] During the Japanese occupation, and when the Indonesian nationalists declared independence on 17 August 1945, the city was renamed Jakarta.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] In 1945, it was briefly occupied by the Allies and returned to the Dutch.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The Dutch name, Batavia, remained the internationally recognized name until Indonesian independence was achieved and Jakarta proclaimed the national capital on 27 December 1949.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Batavia, founded as the trade and administrative center of the VOC, was never intended to be a Dutch settlement.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Jan Pieterszoon Coen founded Batavia for trade, with the city's inhabitants producing and supplying food.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] There was no migration of intact Dutch families, and there were few Dutch women in Batavia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] A mixed society was formed; relationships between Dutchmen and Asian women did not usually result in marriage, and the women did not have the right to return to the Dutch Republic.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] This societal pattern created a group of mestizos in Batavia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Since the VOC preferred to maintain complete control of its business, a large number of slaves was employed.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Women became an important feature of Batavia's social network; they were accustomed to dealing with slaves, and spoke the same language (mostly Portuguese and Malay).
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Many of these women effectively became widows; their husbands left Batavia to return to the Netherlands, and their children were often removed as well.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Most of Batavia's residents were of Asian descent.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Thousands of slaves were brought from India and Arakan; later, slaves were brought from Bali and Sulawesi.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] To avoid an uprising, a decision was made to free the Javanese people from slavery.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Chinese people made up the largest group in Batavia (most being merchants and laborers), and were the most decisive group in the city's development.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Other residents included Malays and Muslim and Hindu merchants from India.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Initially, these ethnic groups lived together; however, in 1688, segregation was imposed on the indigenous population.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Each ethnic group was forced to live in its own village outside the city wall.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Each person was tagged to identify their ethnic group; later, the identity tags were replaced with parchment.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Batavia experienced more malaria epidemics during the 18th century, as its marsh areas bred mosquitoes.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The disease killed many Europeans and Batavia received the nickname "cemetery of Europeans".
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Wealthier European settlers moved to southern areas at higher elevations.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Within Batavia's walls, the wealthy Dutch built tall houses and canals.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Commercial opportunities attracted Indonesian and Chinese immigrants, with the increasing population imposing a burden on the city.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] During the 18th century, over 60 percent of Batavia's population were slaves working for the VOC.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Laws protected slaves against overly cruel actions by their masters; Christian slaves were freed after the death of their masters, and other slaves were allowed to own a store and earn money to buy their freedom.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Although Batavia became the political and administrative center of the Dutch East Indies and the main port in Southeast Asian trade, the city's population remained relatively small.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Early-19th-century estimates of its population were smaller than that of Surabaya, although it overtook the latter by the end of the century; the 1920 census indicated a population of 306,000, compared to 192,000 for Surabaya, 158,000 for Semarang and 134,000 for Surakarta.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Its population increased rapidly, exceeding half a million ten years later.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] The population of the Dutch East Indies was never purely European.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Of the 30,000 Dutch citizens in the Dutch East Indies in 1860, less than 5,000 were purely Dutch.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Seventy percent of the population was male, since more male immigrants arrived from Europe.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Slavery existed in Batavia until its abolition in 1853.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Slaves mainly lived in the back of the garden of the main house and were paid, with free food and lodging.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Female slaves, known as *baboe*, cooked and cared for children.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Children went to school, where the teachers were locally trained.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Many children did not finish school; to counter this, the school system awarded prizes to well-performing children.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] When Stamford Raffles was governor of Java, he changed social interaction in Batavian society.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Raffles disapproved of the relaxed Dutch dress code, where many men wore Javanese attire.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Raffles and his wife, Olivia, introduced European dress (with much white, because of the tropical climate) for men and women.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] When the British left Batavia in 1815, most of the native people reverted to their original Javanese attire but some new aspects persisted.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Native males chosen to be the governing elite wore a European outfit on duty, but after hours they would change to sarongs and kebaya.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Lower-ranked Dutchmen might wear the local style all day.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/batavia-dutch-east-indies] Women wore sarongs and kebaya to official events, where they wore tighter-fitting robes or richly colored (or flowered) cloth—in the style of British India—and batik shawls.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/beer-in-indonesia] The history of **beer in Indonesia** started in 1929, when the Heineken beer company established its first brewery factory in Surabaya, East Java, during Dutch colonial rule of Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/beer-in-indonesia] This was one of the earliest beer enterprise in Southeast Asia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/beer-in-indonesia] In July 1931 the Archipel Brouwerij Compagnie (Archipelago Brewery Co.) was formed in Batavia (now known as Jakarta), by German brewer, Beck's, constructing breweries in both Singapore and Batavia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/beer-in-indonesia] By 1960s, Indonesians developed their own local brands of beer, which includes Bintang Beer (nationalized from Heineken) and Anker Beer.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/beer-in-indonesia] As a Muslim majority country, alcohol industry faces ongoing opposition from Islamic parties and extremist groups in the country.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/beer-in-indonesia] Islamic dietary law prescribed prohibition against alcohol consumption.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/beer-in-indonesia] Because of various regulations, alcohol sales are declining in Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/beer-in-indonesia] Currently, PT Multi Bintang Indonesia Tbk is the largest domestic brewery of Indonesia, with its Bintang Beer leading the market as the largest selling beer of Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/beer-in-indonesia] Multi Bintang Indonesia lead the Indonesian beer market with a commanding total volume share of over 61% in 2012.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/beer-in-indonesia] In 2011, Bintang Beer won the Gold Medal for Lager Beer Category and awarded 'Champion Beer 2011' at the world's class beer competition, the Brewing Industry International Award (BIIA 2011) in London.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/beer-in-indonesia] In 2014 Bintang Radler was introduced which was the first flavoured beer produced domestically in Indonesia.
[src:beer-in-indonesia/beer-in-indonesia] Indonesia also produced under license other brands including San Miguel Beer and Asahi beer.
